05931nam a22008295i 9781487579463DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191974onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875794637 a10.3138/97814875794632doi  a(DE-B1597)527842  a(OCoLC)1129142125  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHM101b.T48 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a301.2400aThinking About Change /ced. by David Shugarman. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1974  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: changing our assumptions about change -- tBetween body and thought -- tMarx on human emancipation -- tBetween memory and dream -- tRhetoric and violence: some considerations of the events of October 1970 -- tPolitical judgment and the viability of institutions -- tThe false imperatives of technology -- tWrong turn: youth and social change -- tVoluntary associations: the view from radical humanism -- tProfessionalism vs Parkdale -- tThe political cornucopia of participation in a movement-party: a brief introduction -- tParticipation vs Parliament -- tContributors -- tBooks by the University League for Social Reform0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe momentum of institutional, attitudinal, and environmental change in western society has accelerated to such a degree that the processes of social evolution appear to be out of control. In the past, social change has been legitimated in terms of progress towards prosperity and freedom but now the disadvantages produced are as great as the advantages. This book of essays by members of the University League for Social Reform is sharply critical of liberal attitudes to social change. Carefully and deliberately written the essays challenge popularly held notions of change; they are stimulating, provocative, and liberating. The first three essays, focusing on the socio-psychological realm of politics, explore the contributions of Freud, Marx, and Marcuse to the central question of what constitutes man's humanity. These are followed by an analysis of the FLQ crisis of 1970 from an Aristotelian point of view and an argument in favour of de Tocqueville's theory of institutional viability over Marx's theory of change. Two essays direct attention to some of the problems associated with technological determinism. The final group of essays focuses attention more directly on social change in Canada, offering an analysis of interest groups and their impact on Canadian society, discussing the satisfactions of belonging to a movement-party, delineating the problems of reorienting legal series to the advantage of the less privileged, and outlining the way the game of parliamentary democracy is played in Canada. The contributors are: Howard Adelman, Mildred Bakan, Barry Cooper, Melvyn Hill, Gerry Hunnius, Alkis Kontos, Bentley Le Baron, William Leiss, James St John, Joan WIlliams, Donald Willmott, and David Shugarman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSocial change. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aAdelman, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBakan, Mildred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Melvyn A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunnius, Gerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKontos, Alkis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLe Baron, Bentley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeiss, Willi